1. Define Your Niche

Decide what type of cleaning service you want to offer:

  • Residential (homes, apartments)

  • Commercial (offices, retail stores)

  • Specialty (carpet cleaning, post-construction, move-in/move-out, Airbnb turnovers)

2. Research and Planning

  • Local Market Research: Understand your competition, pricing, and customer needs.

  • Business Plan: Define your services, pricing, marketing strategy, startup costs, and goals.

3. Legal & Administrative Setup

  • Register Your Business: Choose a name and register it (LLC, sole proprietorship, etc.).

  • Licensing & Insurance: Check local requirements and get liability insurance.

  • Bank Account: Open a separate business account.

4. Supplies and Equipment

  • Purchase cleaning supplies, uniforms, and equipment based on your services.

  • Consider eco-friendly products if that matches your brand.

5. Pricing and Packages

  • Set competitive rates (hourly or flat rate).

  • Offer discounts for recurring services or referrals.

6. Marketing

  • Build a simple website or landing page.

  • Use Google My Business, Yelp, and social media to attract local clients.

  • Offer initial discounts to get your first reviews.

7. Operations

  • Decide if you’ll work solo or hire a team.

  • Use scheduling tools (like Jobber, Housecall Pro) to manage clients and bookings.

  • Create checklists and standards for quality control.

Great! Starting a residential cleaning service is a smart move—homeowners, renters, and landlords often need help with routine and deep cleaning.

Here's how to launch a residential cleaning business step-by-step:

✅ Step 1: Define Your Services

Offer clear, specific packages. For example:

  • Standard Cleaning (weekly/bi-weekly/monthly)

    • Dusting, vacuuming, mopping, kitchen & bathroom wipe-downs

  • Deep Cleaning

    • Behind/under furniture, baseboards, inside appliances, etc.

  • Move-In/Move-Out Cleaning

    • Full detail cleaning for new tenants or property listings

  • Add-ons (extra fee)

    • Inside fridge/oven, laundry, windows, organizing

✅ Step 2: Name and Register Your Business

  • Business Name Ideas: Make it simple and memorable, e.g., Sparkly Nest Cleaning, Fresh Start Homes, or Tidy Touch Residential.

  • Register your business name and apply for any licenses required in your city or state.

✅ Step 3: Get Insurance

  • Liability insurance protects you if something breaks or gets damaged.

  • Optional: bonding (for client trust) and workers' comp (if you hire help).

✅ Step 4: Buy Your Equipment & Supplies

Start with:

  • Microfiber cloths, sponges, gloves, mop, vacuum, duster

  • All-purpose cleaner, disinfectant, glass cleaner, degreaser

  • Bucket or tote bag to carry your supplies

✅ Step 5: Pricing Structure

Here’s a general idea (you’ll adjust based on your local market):

  • Standard cleaning: $80–$150 per home

  • Deep cleaning: $200–$400

  • Hourly rate: $25–$50/hour

You can charge flat fees or hourly, depending on the job size.

✅ Step 6: Get Your First Clients

  • Friends and family: Offer a discount in exchange for testimonials

  • Flyers and door hangers in neighborhoods

  • Facebook Groups, Nextdoor, and Google My Business

  • Ask satisfied clients for referrals and online reviews

✅ Step 7: Manage Bookings & Payments

Start simple with tools like:

  • Google Calendar for appointments

  • Square or PayPal for invoicing/payments

  • Later, use apps like Jobber or BookingKoala for automation

Great! Let’s go through how to get your site online using GitHub Pages or Netlify. Both are free and easy to use.

Option 1: Publish via GitHub Pages

Here’s how you can publish it with GitHub Pages:

  1. Create a GitHub Account (if you don’t already have one):

    • Go to GitHub and create an account.

  2. Create a New Repository:

    • Once logged in, click the “+” icon at the top-right and select New repository.

    • Name your repository (e.g., fresh-nest-cleaning), and click Create repository.

  3. Upload Your Website Files:

    • On the new repository page, click Add file > Upload files.

    • Upload your index.html, red_bird_logo.png, and any other files you have.

    • After uploading, click Commit changes to save them.

  4. Enable GitHub Pages:

    • Go to the Settings tab of your repository.

    • Scroll down to GitHub Pages under the “Pages” section.

    • Select the main branch (if it's not already selected), and click Save.

    • GitHub will give you a link like https://yourusername.github.io/fresh-nest-cleaning.

  5. Access Your Site:

    • After a few minutes, you can visit the link and see your website live!

Option 2: Publish via Netlify

Netlify is even simpler for beginners:

  1. Sign Up for Netlify:

    • Go to Netlify and sign up for a free account.

  2. Create a New Site:

    • After logging in, click New site from Git.

    • Choose GitHub and authorize Netlify to access your GitHub account.

  3. Deploy Your Site:

    • Select the GitHub repository you created earlier (with your website files).

    • Click Deploy Site.

    • Netlify will automatically build and publish your site, and will give you a custom URL (e.g., https://fresh-nest-cleaning.netlify.app).

Any Questions?

Would you like more detailed guidance on either of these steps? Feel free to ask if you run into anything!
